(8026, 'jfxw1', '2016-06-22 13:10:08', 't_mid.1466504319790:588cc327ba1e691765', 'o', '4', 'mvasantos@uplbosa.org', '[Staff Comment]: @channel\r\n\r\nUser background info:\r\nMr. Lester Altoveros is a former instructor of IMSP-CAS. He graduated magna cum laude in 2004 under the BS Applied Physics program. He is currently a senior software developer at Oberthur Technologies.\r\n\r\nMy opinion:\r\nThe Top 20 list is based on GWA similar to how the university determines the valedictorian and salutatorian. I believe that the purpose of posting this list is to congratulate these students (and maybe to publicize the OSA Facebook page). I agree that "such ranking does not factor in the different metrics used to determine the grades used in computing/[coming up] of the [students\'] grades." Such a metric does not exist. The university only releases GWAs as a way to quantifiably measure the performance of each student and that, I believe, was the basis of the Top 20 list.\r\n\r\nIt definitely will elicit comparison of graduates from different colleges - similar to the valedictorian and salutatorian titles. GWA, a single metric used to evaluate performance, is computed for everyone and it can be used by anyone to rank graduates whether OSA congratulates them or not.\r\n\r\nThe user implied that comparison of graduates from different degree programs is a bit "off" because different metrics are used and the total number of units of the degree programs may be different. Because of academic freedom and the freedom for students to choose which electives and sections to enlist in, it is true that different metrics are used for each course taught by each professor. Thus, it is highly unlikely for any two graduating students to have been subjected to the same "metrics" throughout his/her degree program. In the university, GWA is the metric.\r\n\r\nWill they be receiving a special award? They are most probably laude graduates so I believe they have a formal/official award.\r\n\r\nShall OSA take down this post? You may need to consult your supervisor regarding this. In my opinion, there is no need to take down this post because who OSA congratulates is OSA\'s discretion.\r\n\r\nHow I would respond:\r\nHi Lester! We value and respect your opinon and we have noted your concern regarding our Facebook post. For more information about OSA services, visit www.uplbosa.org. Thank you!', '', '', ''),
